I think a lot about the fact that Millennials were the last generation able to build relationships with artists without being expected to critically evaluate them.
We grew up in a golden age of the media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because back then it was simply not easy to determine that.
We didn't have to question the pedestal on which we placed them. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
While "The Office" was on air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
That was completely different from today's streaming era, where 12 episodes come out all at once, and everyone watches whenever they feel like, and they post social media warnings with "spoiler alerts" or discuss them in closed groups.
Unconsciously, we long for this universal community that once ruled everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," in which so many one-liners could be memes today.
We have brought all these sayings, and we assumed that most of them already understood them.
Today, one cannot even assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads virally.
There is far too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Are we even going to be able to get out of this oversaturation again?
We are trapped in a vicious cycle of constantly discovering new content, only to realize later that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must hold on to our nostalgia while at the same time accepting that the people who created the works we like may also have made major mistakes.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes along the way.
Since our collective consciousness regarding media has faded, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who lift someone onto a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a phase of transition, and I'm looking forward to seeing where it will all lead in the end.
